00:14:31.990 --> 00:14:32.990
Look at that beauty.

00:14:40.012 --> 00:14:41.615
-You work in sugar?
-Yes sir.

00:14:41.615 --> 00:14:44.049
So that's mostly everyone in town right?

00:14:44.049 --> 00:14:45.070
Mostly yes.

00:14:45.070 --> 00:14:48.793
That's probably the number one area
for employment here.

00:14:49.042 --> 00:14:52.755
They got Walmart and stuff like that
but it's mainly US sugar.

00:14:52.755 --> 00:14:56.684
And you can live in a nice home with
beautiful streets here working in sugar?

00:14:56.919 --> 00:14:58.972
Yep. As long as you're dedicated.

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:02.970
[Peter] And so these sugar jobs
are just long running jobs?

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:05.189
Like people get in it and they stay in it?

00:15:05.189 --> 00:15:06.189
Yeah most likely.

00:15:06.620 --> 00:15:09.630
There's a lot of people that went there
right after high school.

00:15:09.922 --> 00:15:11.008
And they're still there.

00:15:11.008 --> 00:15:12.548
Now they have homes, families.

00:15:13.458 --> 00:15:15.258
-So it's a good life out here?
-Yeah.

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:19.577
Now there's more risk of everything
else happening, you know, car accidents,

00:15:20.299 --> 00:15:24.053
house burglaries,
or car getting broken into.

00:15:24.480 --> 00:15:26.059
-And you're not feeling it out here?

00:15:26.059 --> 00:15:28.819
It increases the risk
but here in a small town,

00:15:30.361 --> 00:15:31.361
nothing.

00:15:31.703 --> 00:15:32.703
At least for me.

00:15:32.703 --> 00:15:34.453
-Good place for raising kids.
-Yeah.

00:15:34.717 --> 00:15:36.117
Good place for raising kids.

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:45.141
[Peter] Sugar brings in money.
That's for sure.

00:15:45.982 --> 00:15:49.888
It's got a lot of lobbying power
in the US government.

00:15:50.381 --> 00:15:53.020
And it's got a lot of sway.
It's got a lot of weight.

00:15:53.770 --> 00:15:56.826
And you could do a whole sugar story.
And I think many have.

00:15:57.446 --> 00:15:58.966
But that's not really my wheelhouse.

00:15:58.966 --> 00:16:02.680
I don't know enough about sugar
to speak credibly on it.

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:03.964
Other than the basics.

00:16:04.397 --> 00:16:08.968
I've just taken a fascination
about the modern day company town concept.

00:16:09.035 --> 00:16:12.168
I've done a couple of videos in Arizona
in the copper mining towns

00:16:12.168 --> 00:16:14.815
that are completely owned by one company.

00:16:15.141 --> 00:16:18.581
This obviously isn't that.
For example people can buy property here.

00:16:18.808 --> 00:16:20.660
And in a company town you can only rent.

00:16:20.660 --> 00:16:24.828
But there's something interesting
about the lifestyle of the people

00:16:24.828 --> 00:16:27.768
who are all tied into one industry
to some degree.

00:16:35.822 --> 00:16:39.309
Lake Okeechobee,
the second biggest freshwater lake

00:16:39.959 --> 00:16:42.538
in the contiguous United States.

00:16:42.900 --> 00:16:45.650
And many say, and the Internet says,

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:48.385
the best bass fishing of anywhere.

00:16:48.385 --> 00:16:50.267
I'm sure that's up for argument.

00:16:50.594 --> 00:16:52.897
But a lot of bass boats out here going out.

00:16:53.297 --> 00:16:57.463
Lake's massive. Looks like an ocean.
You can't see the other side of it.

00:17:07.847 --> 00:17:10.730
This part of town
is right next to Clewiston.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:12.594
I think it's a different town,

00:17:13.003 --> 00:17:14.003
Harlem.

00:17:14.736 --> 00:17:17.097
We have a monster truck here, jacked up.

00:17:17.097 --> 00:17:18.643
[diesel engine revs]

00:17:20.655 --> 00:17:23.205
You can see the sugar plant
in the background there.

00:17:23.941 --> 00:17:25.991
So I'm guessing all of these people here

00:17:26.495 --> 00:17:29.519
also work for US Sugar… guessing.

00:17:29.825 --> 00:17:32.525
There's not much information
on this town. I gotta say.

00:17:33.038 --> 00:17:34.572
There's really not much.

00:17:36.910 --> 00:17:38.754
Harlem… what's that?

00:17:38.754 --> 00:17:41.040
A movie theater back in the day down there?

00:17:42.447 --> 00:17:45.021
Total opposite
of the other side of the road.

00:17:46.415 --> 00:17:47.748
Got a party lounge.

00:17:48.976 --> 00:17:50.576
Yeah. A little rundown over here.

00:17:52.333 --> 00:17:54.366
Camera down. Getting some hard looks.

00:17:55.643 --> 00:17:56.643
That's alright.

00:17:58.076 --> 00:18:00.529
Bar's on windows.
Wow. It just totally changed.

00:18:01.450 --> 00:18:03.930
Harlem's got some nice homes
but some rundown stuff too.

00:18:03.930 --> 00:18:05.963
So there's always more than you think.

00:18:05.963 --> 00:18:06.930
That is for sure.

00:18:07.351 --> 00:18:09.274
I'm an outsider not an expert.

00:18:09.274 --> 00:18:12.141
Do my best to show you guys what I see.

00:18:12.468 --> 00:18:16.208
Because with video making
I could just show the nicest homes

00:18:16.208 --> 00:18:19.446
or I could just show
the most blighty stuff possible.

00:18:19.793 --> 00:18:21.843
And that's what you'd walk away thinking.

00:18:22.232 --> 00:18:25.198
And so I try to get absolutely everything.

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:29.680
[woman] We are a brand new
Jamaican restaurant.

00:18:29.680 --> 00:18:31.142
-This is your father?
-Yes.

00:18:31.523 --> 00:18:32.545
-Hey!
-Nice.

00:18:32.545 --> 00:18:34.883
-He's the owner. We're both the owners.
-Nice.

00:18:34.883 --> 00:18:36.680
So we're in Harlem right now.

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:38.442
-It's not Clewiston.
-No.

00:18:38.442 --> 00:18:40.068
-It's a different town.
-Yes.

00:18:40.068 --> 00:18:42.387
-Gotcha.
-Yes. We're more in the county. Yes.

00:18:42.675 --> 00:18:44.575
Does everyone here work for sugar?

00:18:44.902 --> 00:18:45.902
Most people do.

00:18:45.902 --> 00:18:48.397
-That's the big employer. Everything.
-Biggest employer.

00:18:48.397 --> 00:18:50.443
I want to say you worked for sugar. Yeah.

00:18:50.443 --> 00:18:51.643
For a long time.

00:18:51.643 --> 00:18:52.935
-28 years.
-28 years.

00:18:53.969 --> 00:18:55.218
Are you still doing it?

00:18:55.218 --> 00:18:56.677
-I retired.
-You retired.

00:18:57.111 --> 00:18:58.837
-How was it?
-It was good.

00:18:58.837 --> 00:19:00.730
-It was good.
-Good, good, good.

00:19:00.730 --> 00:19:03.951
He supported our family very
well off of US Sugar. Yeah.

00:19:04.260 --> 00:19:06.312
-So in a way it's like a company town.

00:19:06.312 --> 00:19:08.049
Yeah. Honestly it is.

00:19:08.049 --> 00:19:09.329
-Okay.
-It is. Yeah.

00:19:09.789 --> 00:19:11.429
This is our restaurant.

00:19:11.429 --> 00:19:13.350
We do have a lot of activities
going on the side.

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:15.390
Because this is where
people hang out a lot.

00:19:15.390 --> 00:19:16.690
We know how to party here.

00:19:16.690 --> 00:19:19.434
You're bringing
the Jamaican vibe to Harlem.

00:19:19.434 --> 00:19:21.009
-Yes, we're bringing the Jamaican vibe.

00:19:21.009 --> 00:19:22.593
-But you grew up here?
-Absolutely.

00:19:23.292 --> 00:19:26.203
-Show us what's going on in here.
-This is our new establishment.

00:19:26.468 --> 00:19:28.629
-Brand spanking new.
-Brand spanking new.

00:19:28.629 --> 00:19:32.109
We renovated everything.

00:19:33.470 --> 00:19:34.570
You okay.

00:19:34.570 --> 00:19:36.012
-And so you're doing a lot to go.

00:19:36.012 --> 00:19:37.212
-Thank you.
-Yes. Mm-hmm.

00:19:38.479 --> 00:19:40.039
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

00:19:40.625 --> 00:19:42.375
[woman] I'm going to see you later.

00:19:43.690 --> 00:19:44.690
[Peter] Oxtail?

00:19:45.410 --> 00:19:46.789
Oh yeah. Nice.

00:19:47.883 --> 00:19:49.253
Making soup.

00:19:49.336 --> 00:19:50.336
Jamaican style.

00:19:51.709 --> 00:19:52.876
-You make this?
-Yeah.

00:19:54.929 --> 00:19:57.135
Oh yeah.
That's plenty. That's plenty.

00:19:57.382 --> 00:19:58.700
It smells delicious.

00:19:58.700 --> 00:19:59.702
-It is delicious.

00:20:01.470 --> 00:20:03.973
Can I give you the camera?
I'll show the food. Okay.

00:20:05.446 --> 00:20:06.620
[woman] Sweet potato.

00:20:06.620 --> 00:20:07.769
-Oh yeah.

00:20:07.769 --> 00:20:09.632
Rich, rich, hearty broth.

00:20:10.086 --> 00:20:11.636
What bone do you have in there?

00:20:11.893 --> 00:20:12.962
-Oh, cow feet.

00:20:12.962 --> 00:20:14.618
Cow feet? It's cow feet.

00:20:14.618 --> 00:20:15.908
-Okay. Yeah.
-Yeah.

00:20:16.756 --> 00:20:18.756
[woman] It's really delicious. Right?

00:20:18.756 --> 00:20:19.756
The coconut milk.

00:20:20.722 --> 00:20:22.576
Coconut milk. That's what's doing it.

00:20:22.979 --> 00:20:24.043
Red peas.

00:20:24.043 --> 00:20:25.162
-Yellow yam.

00:20:26.546 --> 00:20:27.930
Sweet potato.

00:20:27.930 --> 00:20:28.930
Mmm…

00:20:30.169 --> 00:20:31.782
-You know what you're doing.
-Yeah.

00:20:31.782 --> 00:20:32.782
Pro.

00:20:33.130 --> 00:20:35.550
We have natural born
Jamaicans cooking this food.

00:20:36.203 --> 00:20:37.962
Okay. Jamaican's finest.

00:20:38.272 --> 00:20:40.192
Alright, everyone out there,
you gotta come here.

00:20:40.192 --> 00:20:44.530
This is quite possibly
one of the best soups I've had.

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:46.190
-Thank you.
-Yeah, fact.

00:20:46.430 --> 00:20:48.443
So good work on that. Thank you.

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:53.800
Actually, I'm digging this over here.

00:20:54.201 --> 00:20:55.258
Driving through is…

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:58.447
You know, cameras,
people are always wondering, you know,

00:20:58.447 --> 00:21:01.397
why do you have a camera up?
And it's understandable, fully.

00:21:01.623 --> 00:21:04.223
But I told them what I was doing
and they are so cool

00:21:04.223 --> 00:21:05.983
and invited me in

00:21:05.984 --> 00:21:07.969
and showed everything off.

00:21:07.969 --> 00:21:10.789
So, support these guys
if you're in the neighborhood.

00:21:11.382 --> 00:21:12.632
It's called Island Vibes.

00:21:17.121 --> 00:21:19.567
Interesting place,
then you have this new construction

00:21:21.167 --> 00:21:22.967
Right up the road it seems like

00:21:24.027 --> 00:21:27.669
this area is on the up overall I would say.

00:21:28.567 --> 00:21:32.656
As in a feeling of more people
coming into town than leaving.

00:21:34.290 --> 00:21:35.740
Look at those cool buildings.

00:21:36.325 --> 00:21:37.845
We have a church here.

00:21:38.860 --> 00:21:41.390
We have so much ground
to cover today, guys.

00:21:41.390 --> 00:21:43.844
Unfortunately, we're just breezing through,

00:21:44.210 --> 00:21:46.336
but at least it gives you
a bit of a flavor.

00:21:46.776 --> 00:21:48.703
I just love showing juxtaposition.

00:21:49.031 --> 00:21:50.871
First of all, you never know until you go.

00:21:50.871 --> 00:21:54.570
I hear a lot from people like,
I don't have time to travel or the money.

00:21:54.917 --> 00:21:58.912
But in the United States,
so many times if you just drive 45 minutes,

00:21:58.912 --> 00:22:01.306
go into a new town, down a new street,

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:03.987
you run into an experience

00:22:05.080 --> 00:22:06.493
that you wouldn't expect.

00:22:07.394 --> 00:22:10.039
And so you don't need a lot of time.
You don't need a lot of money.

00:22:10.039 --> 00:22:11.939
And then you come back
from a day like today,

00:22:13.190 --> 00:22:17.230
thinking differently about your life,
about where you live.

00:22:18.150 --> 00:22:19.538
I think in a positive way.

00:22:19.538 --> 00:22:22.164
I think all of all of this stuff
goes positively.

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:25.287
And it's just good
to break out of the patterns.

00:22:25.287 --> 00:22:28.602
Break out of going down the same roads,
going to the same places,

00:22:29.330 --> 00:22:31.892
seeing the same faces, but actually

00:22:32.855 --> 00:22:35.202
just a little trip like this today.

00:22:36.249 --> 00:22:37.699
is an interesting experience.

00:22:38.239 --> 00:22:41.892
Alright guys, we gotta get on the road
'cause got some ground to cover.

00:22:41.892 --> 00:22:44.130
Next stop, Immokalee.

00:22:44.659 --> 00:22:47.242
Totally different vibe
from my understanding.

00:22:47.242 --> 00:22:50.059
And then the last destination
is gonna blow your mind.

00:22:50.459 --> 00:22:51.952
Master planned place.

00:22:52.365 --> 00:22:53.715
Religious community.

00:22:54.171 --> 00:22:56.661
Like an oasis out in the middle of nowhere.

00:22:57.210 --> 00:22:58.210
[country music]

00:23:11.336 --> 00:23:15.409
So this is Immokalee and here is primarily

00:23:15.790 --> 00:23:18.804
workers for all the agriculture
around here.

00:23:19.090 --> 00:23:20.970
It's fields and fields forever.

00:23:20.970 --> 00:23:22.504
And then you have Immokalee

00:23:23.137 --> 00:23:24.437
right in the middle of it.

00:23:25.004 --> 00:23:28.692
People think, including myself,
until I started researching this,

00:23:28.692 --> 00:23:31.394
I just think Central California
fruits and vegetables.

00:23:31.394 --> 00:23:33.745
And while it's the biggest player,

00:23:34.060 --> 00:23:37.705
Central Florida is
another massive player for the agriculture.

00:23:38.598 --> 00:23:39.725
Parks are busy.

00:23:40.708 --> 00:23:42.588
BMX bikes, soccer balls.

00:23:43.296 --> 00:23:46.763
I think it's roughly 70% or 80% Latin.
Maybe more.

00:23:47.586 --> 00:23:49.899
Look at that. Beautiful.

00:23:54.497 --> 00:23:56.847
Looks like we got
a little farmer's market here.

00:23:57.413 --> 00:23:59.924
This is a cultural trip, that's for sure.

00:24:00.437 --> 00:24:02.608
It's like true traveling.

00:24:03.756 --> 00:24:05.306
Got a bunch of food carts here.

00:24:06.269 --> 00:24:08.442
Catching the end of the farmer's market.

00:24:09.195 --> 00:24:11.367
Bunch of tables set up for the day,
I'm sure.

00:24:11.740 --> 00:24:14.521
[woman speaking Spanish]

00:24:17.479 --> 00:24:21.740
Okay, the lady didn't want to be on camera,
but she says Saturday's a big work day.

00:24:22.357 --> 00:24:25.604
So this doesn't really come alive
until nighttime.

00:24:26.564 --> 00:24:29.542
And then Sunday, it's just wild here.
It's totally busy.

00:24:30.316 --> 00:24:33.042
But you can see there's just oils,

00:24:33.922 --> 00:24:35.610
bananas, produce,

00:24:36.243 --> 00:24:37.443
toilet paper.

00:24:38.153 --> 00:24:40.928
Whatever you need to live
seems to be out here.

00:24:42.856 --> 00:24:46.966
And she said it's mostly Mexicans
and Guatemalans out here.

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:50.938
So unlike most of Florida,
or at least South Florida,

00:24:51.265 --> 00:24:55.197
I'd say the majority you see
are Cubans or Venezuelans.

00:24:55.745 --> 00:24:57.960
But interior here, the farm workers,

00:24:58.460 --> 00:25:00.520
not really any Cubans or Venezuelans.

00:25:01.760 --> 00:25:02.760
Immokalee.

00:25:03.353 --> 00:25:05.240
Definitely a different Florida.

00:25:05.893 --> 00:25:09.652
I mean, if we're going to compare this
with what's on the coast,

00:25:09.913 --> 00:25:12.762
literally, I don't know, an hour away,

00:25:13.725 --> 00:25:15.384
it's two different universes.

00:25:17.080 --> 00:25:19.780
Show you guys some back roads here,
some neighborhoods.

00:25:20.490 --> 00:25:21.558
And know it's wild.

00:25:21.558 --> 00:25:24.737
I just found this property on Zillow.

00:25:25.220 --> 00:25:26.401
It's a piece of land.

00:25:27.151 --> 00:25:29.651
And it's going to blow your mind
how much it costs.

00:25:30.013 --> 00:25:31.446
Housing's tight here.

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:34.929
It's literally just a small town.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:38.179
Nothing around it on its own.

00:25:38.979 --> 00:25:42.210
So real estate is a premium here.

00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:45.079
Even though looking at some of
these places, you wouldn't think so.

00:25:46.100 --> 00:25:48.200
Alright, let me see if I can find it here.

00:25:49.580 --> 00:25:50.630
I think it's up here.

00:25:51.130 --> 00:25:53.080
But you know what I like
in this neighborhood?

00:25:53.080 --> 00:25:54.982
I gotta say, the streets are a bit alive.

00:25:55.460 --> 00:25:57.485
Like, there is life to the place.

00:25:58.190 --> 00:26:00.113
I'm sure everyone knows everyone.

00:26:01.060 --> 00:26:03.703
They all work together,
live together, go to school together.

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:05.710
Shop together.

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:08.810
It's sort of pleasant walking around,
actually.

00:26:09.525 --> 00:26:10.910
Alright guys, here it is.

00:26:11.180 --> 00:26:12.316
Next to this home.

00:26:13.653 --> 00:26:14.653
Right here.

00:26:16.106 --> 00:26:20.073
This plot,
which is about a third of an acre.

00:26:20.820 --> 00:26:22.038
Guess the cost.

00:26:23.150 --> 00:26:24.370
One third of the acre.

00:26:24.370 --> 00:26:25.706
With the roosters.

00:26:26.187 --> 00:26:27.233
Spanish moss.

00:26:28.227 --> 00:26:29.227
Immokalee

00:26:30.406 --> 00:26:33.338
$180,000.

00:26:33.733 --> 00:26:34.860
You heard me right.

00:26:34.860 --> 00:26:38.709
$180,000 for that piece of land.

00:26:39.456 --> 00:26:43.110
So how much is that place
with a house on it?

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:45.716
That is wild.

00:26:46.970 --> 00:26:50.075
So I read they are really packing in
a lot of these homes.

00:26:50.829 --> 00:26:53.909
Because rents are in demand.

00:26:54.756 --> 00:26:56.706
There's no new building, it looks like.

00:26:57.286 --> 00:26:58.944
And there are plenty of jobs.

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:01.063
So there you go.

00:27:02.120 --> 00:27:03.870
If you're ready to make the move.

00:27:03.870 --> 00:27:05.070
I just found it for you.

00:27:05.432 --> 00:27:06.553
That's wild, huh?

00:27:06.553 --> 00:27:07.844
$180,000 for that?

00:27:09.220 --> 00:27:11.478
And just a lot of places like this.

00:27:11.950 --> 00:27:13.642
Small, simple places.

00:27:14.400 --> 00:27:17.878
And so I read online
that the ag products from this region

00:27:18.465 --> 00:27:20.384
go to 162

00:27:20.977 --> 00:27:22.511
countries and territories.

00:27:23.140 --> 00:27:27.042
A lot of the ag here feeds
the United States too.

00:27:27.386 --> 00:27:28.936
A lot of tomatoes out this way.

00:27:29.587 --> 00:27:31.641
So when you sit down tonight,

00:27:32.080 --> 00:27:33.352
these workers here

00:27:34.209 --> 00:27:38.080
might have picked
the tomatoes on your salad

00:27:38.770 --> 00:27:41.885
or the pasta sauce
that you're enjoying your spaghetti with.

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:43.730
Isn't it wild how that works?

00:27:44.033 --> 00:27:45.033
We're all connected.

00:27:46.501 --> 00:27:48.401
Alright, what's this guy selling here?

00:27:48.887 --> 00:27:49.914
Let's get some of this.

00:27:50.677 --> 00:27:51.677
Is that basil?

00:27:52.873 --> 00:27:53.873
[Spanish]

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:56.379
-Basil?
-No.

00:27:56.946 --> 00:27:59.080
I don't know the name. [Spanish]

00:27:59.080 --> 00:28:00.267
-How much does it cost?

00:28:00.267 --> 00:28:01.327
$3 each.

00:28:01.327 --> 00:28:02.547
Okay. Let's do it.

00:28:03.379 --> 00:28:04.552
-Uno.
-Okay.

00:28:04.552 --> 00:28:05.820
[Spanish]

00:28:05.820 --> 00:28:06.939
Mexico, Oaxaca.

00:28:06.939 --> 00:28:08.412
Oaxaca. Beautiful.

00:28:09.844 --> 00:28:10.838
Oh, nice.

00:28:10.838 --> 00:28:12.120
-Gracias.
-Okay.

00:28:13.202 --> 00:28:14.342
[Spanish]

00:28:15.221 --> 00:28:16.621
Look at that. Three dollars.

00:28:18.160 --> 00:28:20.287
Okay, we have the Mexicana store.

00:28:21.153 --> 00:28:23.120
Looks like a little village market.

00:28:24.140 --> 00:28:25.723
Got some roosters under there.

00:28:37.246 --> 00:28:39.286
Got some good hats for the fields.

00:28:41.694 --> 00:28:42.894
Made in Mexico.

00:28:48.813 --> 00:28:52.513
I'm sure the workers come in, get the food,
go eat out there at the tables.

00:28:54.186 --> 00:28:56.172
Let's see what we got for prices here.

00:28:58.571 --> 00:29:00.569
One and a half pounds, $20.

00:29:02.159 --> 00:29:04.452
That's pretty good. Wow, that's only $6.25.

00:29:06.580 --> 00:29:09.374
$3.23, that is amazing.

00:29:10.735 --> 00:29:11.735
That is cheap.

00:29:13.775 --> 00:29:15.988
$5.05 for all of this, look at that.

00:29:17.673 --> 00:29:19.816
2.67 pounds.

00:29:20.286 --> 00:29:23.811
2.67 pounds. It's got the spice on it.

00:29:25.699 --> 00:29:28.016
$5.05, that is unbelievable.

00:29:37.780 --> 00:29:41.008
Giorgio doesn't want to be on camera,
but he said I could ride his four-Wheeler.

00:29:41.008 --> 00:29:42.907
Thank you, bro. Appreciate it.

00:29:43.598 --> 00:29:44.591
Yeah. There we go.

00:29:44.591 --> 00:29:48.118
[engine cranks and starts]

00:30:01.575 --> 00:30:02.715
This place is great.

00:30:04.521 --> 00:30:08.571
A lot of people don't want to be on camera.
It's too bad. I was just in that shop,

00:30:08.826 --> 00:30:11.223
and they were so cool,

00:30:12.107 --> 00:30:13.571
and I couldn't get them on camera.

00:30:13.571 --> 00:30:15.698
Same with Giorgio,
the dude's four-Wheeler I'm on.

00:30:17.821 --> 00:30:19.371
He said, go take it for a spin.

00:30:30.119 --> 00:30:31.119
Thanks, man.

00:30:39.971 --> 00:30:41.303
So you work at the radio station?

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:43.913
-I work. Yes.
-Okay. How's the town these days?

00:30:43.980 --> 00:30:47.080
Good people. Hard work people.

00:30:47.080 --> 00:30:47.913
-Yeah.

00:30:47.913 --> 00:30:49.882
And it's a nice place.

00:30:49.883 --> 00:30:52.483
They have good players here as well.

00:30:52.483 --> 00:30:53.483
-Players?
-Yes.

00:30:53.483 --> 00:30:54.646
For what? Football?

00:30:54.646 --> 00:30:59.449
They do, I don't know the name in English,
but it's like soccer.

00:30:59.449 --> 00:31:00.981
-Yes. Okay.
-I think soccer.

00:31:01.624 --> 00:31:04.723
-Okay. So most people here
are working in agriculture.

00:31:05.076 --> 00:31:06.076
Yes.

00:31:06.369 --> 00:31:08.936
It's amazing how they can, you know,

00:31:09.195 --> 00:31:12.116
keep this town or the country alive

00:31:12.117 --> 00:31:17.011
because fruits, vegetables,
and everything that is growing here,

00:31:17.410 --> 00:31:18.360
they go everywhere.

00:31:18.992 --> 00:31:20.761
You know, it's family people.

00:31:20.761 --> 00:31:22.268
They are not criminals.

00:31:22.269 --> 00:31:24.491
They are really good people.

00:31:24.491 --> 00:31:27.056
The community is really, really good.

00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:29.606
So, mostly Mexicans?

00:31:30.142 --> 00:31:32.405
Mexicans, Guatemala…

00:31:32.756 --> 00:31:34.136
-No Cubans, no Venezuelans?

00:31:35.409 --> 00:31:36.763
-Some Cubans.
-Okay.

00:31:37.082 --> 00:31:39.371
-I am Dominican.
-You're Dominican? Nice. Cool.

00:31:39.377 --> 00:31:42.288
-And they have Haiti people from here too.
-Okay.

00:31:42.643 --> 00:31:44.469
They could work here as well.

00:31:45.267 --> 00:31:47.620
-It's a whole other Florida out here.
Totally different.

00:31:47.892 --> 00:31:48.902
-It is.

00:31:48.902 --> 00:31:50.873
-It's cool though. Well, thank you.

00:31:51.073 --> 00:31:52.410
You're welcome. Nice to meet you.

00:31:52.410 --> 00:31:54.187
-You're very sweet.
-Thank you.

00:31:54.474 --> 00:31:55.869
Who do I pay here?

00:31:55.869 --> 00:31:57.464
Um, to…

00:31:58.970 --> 00:32:01.755
[Spanish]

00:32:05.876 --> 00:32:08.316
I'm gonna buy the Miss's fruit too.

00:32:11.464 --> 00:32:12.880
-Oh, no, it's not necessary.

00:32:12.881 --> 00:32:14.252
Yeah, I want to.

00:32:14.252 --> 00:32:16.200
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:18.550
-Nice to meet you.
-Take care. You too. Bye-bye.

00:32:18.878 --> 00:32:19.911
Bye-bye, sir.

00:32:23.639 --> 00:32:24.639
Here we go.

00:32:25.719 --> 00:32:26.719
Mmm.

00:32:29.065 --> 00:32:32.365
Guys, I would love to stay in this town
and get a good Mexican meal

00:32:32.679 --> 00:32:34.306
'cause I'm sure there are plenty here.

00:32:34.306 --> 00:32:36.606
But we got to get our last stop
before sundown.

00:32:37.339 --> 00:32:39.198
So I'm tempted but,

00:32:40.758 --> 00:32:42.608
I'm gonna settle for fruit right now.

00:32:43.100 --> 00:32:44.363
And like that woman said,

00:32:45.261 --> 00:32:47.700
Mexicans or Latinos here, they work.

00:32:47.700 --> 00:32:49.856
It's true. I mean, straight up.

00:32:50.752 --> 00:32:52.902
Thank God.
You know, they have a work ethic.

00:32:53.270 --> 00:32:55.628
We would not have fruits and vegetables

00:32:55.628 --> 00:32:58.750
and half the things we eat
without that labor force.

00:32:58.750 --> 00:33:00.606
And what's interesting
about that labor force,

00:33:00.606 --> 00:33:02.318
I don't know how things are working here.

00:33:02.318 --> 00:33:03.353
So I'm not going to

00:33:04.486 --> 00:33:07.390
speak about it
when I don't know the full truth.

00:33:07.390 --> 00:33:11.434
But for example,
the US government has the H2A visa.

00:33:11.434 --> 00:33:15.316
That's a temporary
sort of farm agricultural worker visa.

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:20.958
I believe we're giving out
more than 400,000

00:33:20.959 --> 00:33:22.511
of those a year right now.

00:33:22.511 --> 00:33:25.120
It's gone up in the last couple years.

00:33:25.120 --> 00:33:28.699
So we are giving more of those visas
for people to work here.

00:33:29.065 --> 00:33:32.421
Now, permanent residents,
impossible to know.

00:33:32.421 --> 00:33:36.374
But there is that system
that doesn't get reported on so much.

00:33:36.374 --> 00:33:39.424
As in field workers, farm workers,

00:33:39.712 --> 00:33:41.064
totally here legally,

00:33:41.780 --> 00:33:43.514
and getting that H2A visa.

00:33:43.990 --> 00:33:45.200
I wish there was more of that.

00:33:45.200 --> 00:33:47.804
I wish there were these people…
they come, they work hard,

00:33:48.450 --> 00:33:52.019
and if they add to society, to the country,

00:33:53.075 --> 00:33:54.687
there has to be a limit, obviously.

00:33:54.687 --> 00:33:56.943
But there has to be a pathway of some sort.

00:33:56.943 --> 00:33:59.438
And the H2A visa,
I think, is one way to do it.

00:34:00.230 --> 00:34:02.980
And I need to dig into that more.

00:34:02.980 --> 00:34:08.504
Like what visas the US government
is giving to, say, more permanent

00:34:09.543 --> 00:34:11.278
workers that come up here and work.

00:34:12.053 --> 00:34:13.053
I don't know.

00:34:13.446 --> 00:34:15.326
It's a topic to explore for sure.

00:34:15.946 --> 00:34:16.953
Fruit's good.

00:34:18.446 --> 00:34:19.324
Let's go.

00:34:19.390 --> 00:34:20.390
[country music]

00:34:47.436 --> 00:34:50.026
The camera doesn't fully give this justice.

00:34:50.026 --> 00:34:54.250
But we're literally 10,
okay, max 15 minutes

00:34:54.802 --> 00:34:55.958
away from Immokalee

00:34:56.595 --> 00:34:57.595
to here.

00:34:58.068 --> 00:34:59.068
Ave Maria.

00:34:59.355 --> 00:35:02.520
Founded in 2007 by, get this,

00:35:02.958 --> 00:35:05.110
by the former founder of Domino's,

00:35:05.110 --> 00:35:06.296
Tom Monaghan.

00:35:06.810 --> 00:35:09.060
So he sold his business,
most of it I believe.

00:35:09.670 --> 00:35:11.935
And wanted to start a town.

00:35:12.990 --> 00:35:14.090
So this is a new town.

00:35:14.458 --> 00:35:17.863
Built around the Catholic University here.

00:35:18.647 --> 00:35:20.520
This is like a self-contained,

00:35:20.878 --> 00:35:22.369
removed from everything,

00:35:22.788 --> 00:35:24.282
really posh,

00:35:25.109 --> 00:35:26.109
clean,

00:35:26.988 --> 00:35:28.387
well manicured world.

00:35:29.181 --> 00:35:31.938
This is really a trip today, you guys.

00:35:32.608 --> 00:35:35.758
Just the differences
of each town's identity.

00:35:36.270 --> 00:35:39.338
Let's try to get as much in
before it gets dark.

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:43.347
Okay, I pulled this up.

00:35:44.214 --> 00:35:46.344
"Ave Maria was built on purpose.

00:35:46.344 --> 00:35:48.910
A planned community
designed around faith,

00:35:49.366 --> 00:35:52.494
order, and separation
from the surrounding region.

00:35:53.120 --> 00:35:54.877
Intentional social architecture

00:35:54.878 --> 00:35:57.392
to reinforce shared moral framework

00:35:57.392 --> 00:36:01.300
in a space free from
outside cultural interests."

00:36:01.778 --> 00:36:03.702
So I think they accept everyone here.

00:36:03.702 --> 00:36:05.755
It's not fully Christian.

00:36:05.755 --> 00:36:08.033
But they wanted to create something that

00:36:08.515 --> 00:36:09.815
revolves around the faith.

00:36:10.496 --> 00:36:13.120
So that's why you have that
right in the center of town.

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:16.964
Roughly 6,000 to 7,000 people living here.

00:36:17.390 --> 00:36:18.390
And it's growing.

00:36:19.053 --> 00:36:20.333
Golf cart culture.

00:36:20.820 --> 00:36:24.507
It's got a little bit of The Villages feel,
first impression, but different.

00:36:25.180 --> 00:36:26.180
Let's walk around.

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:29.760
So I guess this is
all the university right over here.

00:36:30.549 --> 00:36:35.095
The university has roughly
1,100 to 1,300 students.

00:36:35.516 --> 00:36:37.400
And also some good high paying jobs.

00:36:37.400 --> 00:36:40.068
Because you have professors working there,

00:36:40.533 --> 00:36:41.533
living here.

00:36:42.363 --> 00:36:43.963
Here we have some of the donors.

00:36:47.409 --> 00:36:48.894
Lights hitting it perfectly.

00:36:55.100 --> 00:36:56.560
[choir singing]

00:37:39.747 --> 00:37:40.747
Peaceful.

00:37:41.286 --> 00:37:42.510
Nice. Beautiful church.

00:37:43.320 --> 00:37:44.492
For a modern church.

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:51.033
There are a lot of languages here too.

00:37:52.700 --> 00:37:54.500
They have a Mexican restaurant here.

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:57.650
I'm going to say
the best Mexican's down the road.

00:37:58.340 --> 00:37:59.340
Melt.

00:37:59.664 --> 00:38:00.634
Vicky Bakery.

00:38:02.100 --> 00:38:03.560
A bunch of new shops.

00:38:04.509 --> 00:38:06.254
Founded in 2007.

00:38:06.254 --> 00:38:08.783
That's an amazing feat.

00:38:10.001 --> 00:38:11.451
That's a lot of construction

00:38:12.721 --> 00:38:13.921
to make all that happen.

00:38:14.730 --> 00:38:16.182
So, Catholic.

00:38:16.767 --> 00:38:18.917
Want to be around a lot of other Catholics.

00:38:19.824 --> 00:38:20.824
Makes sense.

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:22.900
Living in a place like this.

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:26.872
I'm sure it's a cool community out here.

00:38:26.872 --> 00:38:28.772
I'm sure there are events and whatnot.

00:38:29.109 --> 00:38:30.643
You can imagine very safe.

00:38:31.670 --> 00:38:35.140
Don't see an edgy element to this place.

00:38:36.212 --> 00:38:38.188
It's maybe boring for the youth.

00:38:39.053 --> 00:38:40.053
Definitely see that.

00:38:40.594 --> 00:38:42.867
But I'm sure there's
a bunch of stuff going on.

00:38:42.867 --> 00:38:44.767
Just not getting it at the right time.

00:38:45.287 --> 00:38:46.324
It's Saturday.

00:38:46.324 --> 00:38:49.304
So that's Saturday mass going on there.

00:38:50.384 --> 00:38:51.484
Alright, let's cruise.

00:38:53.489 --> 00:38:54.489
[man] Thank you.

00:38:56.264 --> 00:38:57.827
Polite kids. Said thank you.

00:38:58.134 --> 00:38:59.749
That's nice. Good parenting.

00:39:00.340 --> 00:39:02.090
I was at Whole Foods the other day,

00:39:02.903 --> 00:39:05.053
and I stopped for these
young teenage girls.

00:39:05.672 --> 00:39:07.636
Didn't have to. There's no crosswalk.

00:39:08.011 --> 00:39:09.707
And no thank you at all.

00:39:11.270 --> 00:39:15.381
They were probably dressed in
a thousand dollars worth of clothes each.

00:39:15.642 --> 00:39:17.136
So it's nice to see that.

00:39:17.136 --> 00:39:18.586
The thank you from the youth.

00:39:19.341 --> 00:39:20.691
All comes from the parents.

00:39:21.713 --> 00:39:24.286
Alright guys.
So lot of roundabouts here.

00:39:25.013 --> 00:39:26.113
And it just looks like

00:39:27.343 --> 00:39:28.343
a lot of that.

00:39:29.688 --> 00:39:31.730
Lot of homes, waterways.

00:39:33.245 --> 00:39:34.245
Nice lake.

00:39:34.972 --> 00:39:37.026
I mean if predictability, and safety,

00:39:37.356 --> 00:39:41.068
and I guess knowing what's
around every turn is your thing,

00:39:41.068 --> 00:39:42.083
then this is the place.

00:39:45.970 --> 00:39:48.620
[Peter] So you said they're gonna put
a thousand more homes in?

00:39:48.620 --> 00:39:50.107
-A thousand more homes going in.

00:39:50.107 --> 00:39:51.200
-Oh wow.

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:52.970
Yeah, so it's expanding rapidly.

00:39:53.370 --> 00:39:55.770
-How many years have you lived out here?
-Seven years.

00:39:55.770 --> 00:39:57.217
Seven years Christmas.

00:39:57.217 --> 00:39:59.207
-Do you like it?
-It's okay.

00:39:59.550 --> 00:40:01.150
We lived in South Bend, Indiana.

00:40:01.389 --> 00:40:04.657
-Okay.
-We had four distinct seasons.

00:40:04.658 --> 00:40:05.830
We used to enjoy that.

00:40:05.830 --> 00:40:08.639
Yeah, Florida summers are brutal
but what about the community?

00:40:08.639 --> 00:40:10.770
-Do you like the community?
-The community is okay.

00:40:10.770 --> 00:40:11.770
-Yeah.
-Okay.

00:40:13.546 --> 00:40:15.490
-I'm not Catholic.
-You're not Catholic?

00:40:15.490 --> 00:40:16.798
-I'm not Catholic.
-Okay.

00:40:16.798 --> 00:40:18.354
A lot of people aren't Catholic.

00:40:18.354 --> 00:40:21.423
-Okay.
-So we actually attend church in Naples.

00:40:21.870 --> 00:40:24.290
Okay. What denomination are you?

00:40:24.490 --> 00:40:26.530
Well, we're in a Baptist church.

00:40:26.530 --> 00:40:27.570
-Okay.
-Yeah.

00:40:27.570 --> 00:40:29.279
Good place for kids?

00:40:29.279 --> 00:40:31.190
Yeah, very good place for kids.

00:40:31.910 --> 00:40:32.989
This is one right here.

00:40:32.989 --> 00:40:34.728
-This is Junior? Nice.
-This is my grandson.

00:40:34.728 --> 00:40:36.284
-Can I have some juice?
-Yes, you can.

00:40:36.284 --> 00:40:37.284
That's my grandson.

00:40:37.650 --> 00:40:39.665
-Your neighbors are from where?
-Turkey.

00:40:39.665 --> 00:40:42.730
These people were from…
Been here for two years now.

00:40:42.730 --> 00:40:44.380
They were from Columbia.

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:48.053
-But people come here
because they want safe, clean…

00:40:49.122 --> 00:40:51.515
You'll notice as you
travel the community,

00:40:51.515 --> 00:40:54.355
you'll see some police cars from Miami.

00:40:54.648 --> 00:40:55.998
From Dade County and so on.

00:40:56.405 --> 00:40:58.275
I've spoken with several of them.

00:40:58.275 --> 00:41:01.356
They said it was better on me to go to work

00:41:02.186 --> 00:41:05.160
in Miami and know my family is safe here

00:41:05.541 --> 00:41:06.555
in Ave Maria.

00:41:06.555 --> 00:41:08.455
-Are you serious?
-It's about thinking.

00:41:11.015 --> 00:41:13.815
[Peter] Yeah, you just see
a bunch of kids out and about.

00:41:14.512 --> 00:41:16.565
You see a lot of garage doors open.

00:41:19.880 --> 00:41:21.156
Oh, there it is.

00:41:21.156 --> 00:41:22.756
Just what he was saying, police.

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:25.798
That's funny. He called it.
We're a few streets away, too.

00:41:26.706 --> 00:41:27.883
Miami Dade.

00:41:27.883 --> 00:41:30.371
Guy drives, I'm guessing, two hours

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:34.252
just to get into Miami
and keep his family out here.

00:41:35.282 --> 00:41:37.003
So wow. Look at this.

00:41:37.003 --> 00:41:38.833
This is massive.

00:41:39.583 --> 00:41:43.387
Well, it seems like they're not
the only ones that want this.

00:41:44.060 --> 00:41:46.410
This seems to be really growing.

00:41:50.291 --> 00:41:52.007
Oh, that's cute. What is this guy?

00:41:52.308 --> 00:41:54.706
-Carmelo.
-Carmelo. Puppy, yeah?

00:41:54.706 --> 00:41:56.720
He's a Toy Maltese.
He's only nine weeks old.

00:41:57.480 --> 00:41:59.389
-So you all met each other…

00:41:59.389 --> 00:42:00.740
-Yesterday. We were walking.

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:01.740
Okay.

00:42:02.133 --> 00:42:03.233
And they were outside.

00:42:03.620 --> 00:42:06.429
-And how long have you lived here for?
-Since May of last year.

00:42:06.429 --> 00:42:08.323
-Your daughter?
-Yeah. One of them.

00:42:08.323 --> 00:42:10.581
-You guys liking it?
-Mm-hmm. We like it.

00:42:10.894 --> 00:42:11.742
We love it.

00:42:11.742 --> 00:42:13.184
We used to live in Fort Lauderdale.

00:42:13.184 --> 00:42:15.676
Couldn't find a house for
like less than a million dollars,

00:42:15.676 --> 00:42:17.202
so we just came out this way.

00:42:17.202 --> 00:42:18.952
Okay. What are houses for out here?

00:42:19.160 --> 00:42:20.593
Depends. Like, um,

00:42:21.436 --> 00:42:25.762
depends how big, how small, but like mine
basically was like around 550.

00:42:25.762 --> 00:42:26.545
Okay.

00:42:26.545 --> 00:42:27.995
But I have a 4-3 with a pool.

00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:29.990
And you can't get that out there.

00:42:30.170 --> 00:42:34.526
These houses down here on this side,
they got them for 398 I think.

00:42:34.526 --> 00:42:36.678
And they're three bedrooms,
but they don't have pools.

00:42:36.678 --> 00:42:37.379
-Okay.

00:42:37.379 --> 00:42:38.890
But it's pretty affordable.

00:42:38.890 --> 00:42:40.426
What are we doing? We doing a picture?

00:42:40.426 --> 00:42:42.576
-I want to do a picture.
-Okay, let's do it.

00:42:43.882 --> 00:42:45.022
How are we doing this?

00:42:45.022 --> 00:42:46.043
Here.

00:42:46.043 --> 00:42:47.817
-Get on this side.
-Puppy in the middle?

00:42:48.345 --> 00:42:49.345
-Puppy in the middle.

00:42:55.640 --> 00:42:57.477
All right, guys, what a day today.

00:42:57.477 --> 00:42:59.837
And I could have spent a day
in each one of these towns,

00:42:59.838 --> 00:43:01.854
but I wanted to show you the differences

00:43:02.352 --> 00:43:04.773
between the towns here
in South Central Florida,

00:43:05.218 --> 00:43:07.027
ranching up in Okeechobee,

00:43:07.425 --> 00:43:09.963
Clewiston, straight up sugar industry.

00:43:10.302 --> 00:43:11.302
Immokalee,

00:43:11.630 --> 00:43:12.835
produce, labor.

00:43:13.432 --> 00:43:14.432
Ave Maria,

00:43:14.815 --> 00:43:16.574
faith based. Here for purpose.

00:43:17.320 --> 00:43:19.797
People from all over the world.

00:43:20.330 --> 00:43:22.312
So quite a mix of places.

00:43:22.910 --> 00:43:27.310
In a I'd say pretty much unknown
part of the state and the country.

00:43:27.310 --> 00:43:30.530
So thanks for coming along
on that journey, you guys.

00:43:30.790 --> 00:43:31.790
Until the next one.

